# Meet Campus - Copilot Instructions

## Project Overview

This is a **Blazor WebAssembly** web application with a hosted ASP.NET Core backend using .NET 10, Entity Framework Core with PostgreSQL, and Tailwind CSS for styling. The project follows a **vertical slicing architecture** with modern C# patterns and best practices.

## Technology Stack

- **Framework:** Blazor WebAssembly (Interactive Mode) + ASP.NET Core Backend
- **.NET Version:** .NET 10
- **Database:** PostgreSQL with Entity Framework Core
- **Styling:** Tailwind CSS (mobile-first)
- **Authentication:** ASP.NET Core Identity with Blazor auth patterns
- **Real-Time Messaging:** SignalR (for chat)
- **Language:** C# 14 (prefer C# for all client-side logic; avoid JavaScript)

## Project Type

**Social/Dating App** with real-time friend discovery, connections, and messaging capabilities.


## Architecture & Project Structure

- Use vertical slicing: organize by feature (Auth, Users, Connections, Chat, Notifications, etc.), not by technical layer.
- Each feature contains its own Pages, Services, DTOs, Components, and (if needed) Hubs.
- Shared components and services go in a Shared folder.
- Each class, interface, DTO, and component must be in its own file.

## C# Coding Standards

### Naming Conventions

- **Classes & Interfaces:** PascalCase (`UserService`, `IUserRepository`)
- **Methods & Properties:** PascalCase (`GetUserById()`, `IsActive`)
- **Private fields:** `_camelCase` (e.g., `_logger`, `_userService`)
- **Constants:** `UPPER_SNAKE_CASE` or PascalCase for well-known constants
- **Blazor Components:** PascalCase ending in `.razor` (e.g., `UserCard.razor`, `LoadingSpinner.razor`)
- **DTOs:** `[Entity]Dto` suffix (e.g., `UserDto`, `PostCreateDto`)
- **Services:** `[Entity]Service` suffix (e.g., `UserService`, `PostService`)


### File Organization
- Use one file per class, interface, DTO, or component.


### Modern C# 14 Patterns
- Use file-scoped namespaces, records for DTOs, and nullable reference types.
- Prefer `required` for mandatory properties and use async/await throughout.

## Entity Framework Core & PostgreSQL


### Core Social App Entities
- User: profile, bio, photo, age, gender, interests, last seen, etc.
- Connection: friend requests, matches, blocks, status, timestamps.
- ChatMessage: sender, recipient, content, sent/read timestamps, isRead.


**DbContext Setup:**
- Entities go in `Data/Entities/` folder.
- Use PostgreSQL provider and migrations for schema changes.

### DTOs vs Entities

- **Entities:** Only in `Data/Entities/`. Used by EF Core and database layer only.
- **DTOs:** In `Features/[Feature]/DTOs/`. Used for API responses and service communication.
- **Never expose entities directly** from APIs or services; always map to DTOs.


**DTOs:**
- Use DTOs for all API/service communication. Never expose entities directly.

### Async All the Way

- All database operations must be **async**
- Use `async`/`await` end-to-end
- Use `CancellationToken` parameter (default: `CancellationToken ct = default`)
- Example:

```csharp
public async Task<UserDto?> GetUserByIdAsync(int id, CancellationToken ct = default)
{
    var user = await _context.Users
        .AsNoTracking()
        .FirstOrDefaultAsync(u => u.Id == id, ct);
    
    return user == null ? null : MapToDto(user);
}
```

## Blazor WebAssembly & Interactive Mode

### Component Organization

**Interactive WebAssembly Components:**
- Location: `Features/[Feature]/Components/`
- Render mode: Add `@rendermode InteractiveWebAssembly` to components that need interactivity
- Use static rendering for layout/non-interactive components

**Component Structure:**

```razor
@page "/users/{UserId:int}"
@rendermode InteractiveWebAssembly
@using MeetCampus.Features.Users.Services
@using MeetCampus.Features.Users.DTOs
@inject UserService UserService
@inject NavigationManager Navigation

<div class="container mx-auto p-4">
    @if (user == null)
    {
        <LoadingSpinner />
    }
    else
    {
        <h1 class="text-2xl font-bold">@user.FirstName @user.LastName</h1>
    }
</div>

@code {
    [Parameter]
    public int UserId { get; set; }

    private UserDto? user;

    protected override async Task OnInitializedAsync()
    {
        user = await UserService.GetUserByIdAsync(UserId);
    }
}
```


### Authentication in Blazor
- Use CascadingAuthenticationState and AuthorizeView for authentication.

```razor
<AuthorizeView>
    <Authorized>
        <p>Welcome, @context.User.Identity?.Name</p>
    </Authorized>
    <NotAuthorized>
        <p>You are not authorized</p>
    </NotAuthorized>
</AuthorizeView>
```


### Prefer C# Over JavaScript
- Use C# for all client-side logic. Avoid JavaScript unless absolutely necessary.


## SignalR for Real-Time Chat
- Use SignalR for all real-time chat and notifications.
- Place server-side hubs in each feature's Hubs folder.
- Use a client-side wrapper service for SignalR in Blazor.
- Use group management for targeted message delivery.


## Styling with Tailwind CSS
- Use Tailwind CSS for all styling.
- Design mobile-first, then add responsive breakpoints.
- Use reusable components for common UI patterns.

## Dependency Injection


### Service Registration Pattern
- Register all services and SignalR hubs using dependency injection in Program.cs.


### Injecting into Components
- Use constructor or property injection for services in Blazor components.


### Service Design
- Keep services focused on one responsibility. Use scoped lifetime by default.

## Error Handling & Validation


### Null Checks
- Use ArgumentNullException and input validation for all parameters.


### Exception Types
- Use specific exceptions and provide meaningful error messages.


### Async Exception Handling
- Log and handle exceptions gracefully in async code.


## Logging
- Use ILogger<T> for logging. Use appropriate log levels and structured data.


## API Layer (Backend)
- Group endpoints by feature. Use DTOs for all input/output.


## Testing Best Practices
- Create a separate test project. Test public APIs and services. Use xUnit or similar.

## Security Best Practices

### Social App Specific

- **User Privacy:** Never expose user data (email, phone) without explicit permission
- **Block List:** Always check if users have blocked each other before showing profiles or allowing chat
- **Message Encryption:** Consider end-to-end encryption for private messages in future versions
- **Report/Abuse:** Implement reporting mechanism for inappropriate behavior
- **Age Verification:** Validate user age claims (for dating app context)
- **Photo Moderation:** Implement photo review before public visibility
- **Rate Limiting:** Implement rate limiting on:
  - Connection requests (e.g., max 50 per day)
  - Message sending (e.g., max 100 per hour)
  - Profile views logging

### General Best Practices

- **Never** expose database entities in API responses; use DTOs
- Validate all user input server-side
- Use `[Authorize]` attributes on protected endpoints
- Hash passwords with Identity Core (built-in)
- Use `CancellationToken` to prevent long-running operations
- Store secrets in `appsettings.json` (local dev) or environment variables (production)
- Enable HTTPS everywhere
- Use CSRF protection (already enabled with `app.UseAntiforgery()`)


## Real-Time Notifications
- Use SignalR for new match alerts, message notifications, typing indicators, online/offline status, and connection requests.

